    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"1024069\">Coder-Osman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Master.20theorem.20for.20divide-and-conquer.20recurrences/near/575445023\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I’ll just treat my development as a personal exercise.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Can I suggest solving this TODO in AkraBazzi?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Markdown\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>Specialize this theorem to the very common case where the recurrence is of the form\n  <span class=\"sb\">`T(n) = ℓT(r_i(n)) + g(n)`</span>\n  where <span class=\"sb\">`g(n) ∈ Θ(n^t)`</span> for some <span class=\"sb\">`t`</span>. (This is often called the \"master theorem\" in the literature.)\n</code></pre></div>",
